## NULL
clean_sensor <- function(data, clean_df = cdff, locID = 2, varID = 1, clsetID = 1) {
  #cleaning_set_id;location_id;variable_id;c
  clean_df <- clean_df %>% 
    filter(cleaning_set_id == clsetID) %>%
    filter(location_id == locID) %>% 
    filter(variable_id == varID) %>%
    select(correction, arguments)
  out <- data
  print(clean_df)
  if(nrow(clean_df) > 0) {
    for(i in 1:nrow(clean_df)){
      corr <- clean_df[[i, "correction"]]
      args <- clean_df[[i, "arguments"]]
      
      args_list <- fromJSON(args)
      args_list <- c(list(data=out), args_list)
      out <- do.call(corr, args_list)
    }
    
  }
  return(out)
}

for(loc in dist_locs) {
  res_filt <- 
    res %>% 
    filter(location_id == loc)
  dist_vars <- 
    res_filt %>% distinct(variable_id) %>% unlist()
  
  print(dist_vars)
  # ### map function to clean sensors
  res_clean <- 
    dist_vars %>%
    map(function(x) { 
      res_filt %>% # should be res_filt
        rename("TIMESTAMP" = timestamp) %>%
        rename("Sensor" = value) %>%
        # filter(location_id == x) %>%  # most_likely not needed
        clean_sensor(locID = loc, varID = x) # locID = loc, var_ID = x
    }) %>%
    bind_rows() %>%
    rename("timestamp" = TIMESTAMP,
           "value" = Sensor)
  ###
  g <- 
    res_clean %>%
    ggplot(aes(x=timestamp, y=value, colour = factor(variable_id), group=factor(variable_id))) + 
    facet_wrap(~variable_id, scales = 'free_y') +
    geom_line() + 
    ggtitle(loc) +
    theme_bw() +
    guides(colour = "none")
  plot(g)
}

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:
